1 ENGR OSSED HOUSE AMENDMENT
TO
2 ENGROSSED SENATE BILL NO. 667 By: Coleman of the Senate
3 and
4 Roe and Hays of the House
5
6
7 An Act relating to chiropractors; amending 59 O.S.
2021, Sections 161.2, 161.3, 161.7, 161.8, and 161.9,
8 which relate to the Oklahoma Chiropractic Practice
Act; modifying definitions; requiring use of
9 licensure portals; modifying certain licensing
requirements; modifying requirements for notification
10 of disapproval; updating statutory language;
repealing 59 O.S. 2021, Section 161.12a, which
11 relates to registration as chiropractic claims
consultant; and providing an effective date.
12
13 AUTHORS: Remove Representative Hays as House co-author.
14 AMENDMENT NO. 1. Strike the title, enacting clause, and entire bill
and insert:
15
16
17 "An Act relating to chiropractors; amending 59 O.S.
2021, Sections 161.2, 161.3, 161.7, 161.8, and 161.9,
18 which relate to the Oklahoma Chiropractic Practice
Act; modifying definitions; requiring use of
19 licensure portals; modifying certain licensing
requirements; modifying requirements for notification
20 of disapproval; updating statutory language;
repealing 59 O.S. 2021, Section 161.12a, which
21 relates to registration as chiropractic claims
consultant; and providing an effective date.
22
23
24 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 667 Page 1

1 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 59 O.S. 2021, Section 161.2, is
2 amended to read as follows:
3 Section 161.2. A. Chiropractic is the science and art that
4 teaches health in anatomic relation and disease or abnormality in
5 anatomic disrelation, and includes hygienic, sanitary and
6 therapeutic measures incident thereto in humans. The scope of
7 practice of chiropractic shall include those diagnostic and
8 treatment services and procedures which have been taught by an
9 accredited chiropractic college program and have been approved by
10 the Board of Chiropractic Examiners.
11 B. A chiropractic physician may engage in the practice of
12 animal chiropractic diagnosis and treatment if certified to do so by
13 the Board. A licensed chiropractic physician may provide
14 chiropractic treatment to an animal without being certified in
15 animal chiropractic diagnosis and treatment by the Board if an
16 animal has been referred to the chiropractic physician by a licensed
17 veterinarian in writing.
18 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 59 O.S. 2021, Section 161.3, is
19 amended to read as follows:
20 Section 161.3. As used in the Oklahoma Chiropractic Practice
21 Act, these words, phrases or terms, unless the context otherwise
22 indicates, shall have the following meanings:
23 1. "Accredited chiropractic college program" means a
24 chiropractic educational institution degree program which is
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 667 Page 2

1 accr edited by an accrediting agency recognized by the U.S.
2 Department of Education;
3 2. "Animal chiropractic diagnosis and treatment" means
4 treatment that includes vertebral subluxation complex (vsc) and
5 spinal manipulation of nonhuman vertebrates. The term "animal
6 animal chiropractic diagnosis and treatment" treatment shall not be
7 construed to allow the:
8 a. use of x-rays,
9 b. performing of surgery,
10 c. dispensing or administering of medications, or
11 d. performance of traditional veterinary care;
12 3. "Applicant" means any person submitting an application for
13 licensure to the Board;
14 4. "Board" means the Board of Chiropractic Examiners;
15 5. "Certified chiropractic assistant" means an unlicensed
16 member of a chiropractic physician's team of healthcare workers who
17 may assist a chiropractic physician in the performance of
18 examination and therapeutic procedures and techniques necessary to
19 deliver healthcare services to patients within the scope of
20 chiropractic and has been certified by the Board;
21 6. "Chiropractic physician", "chiropractor", "doctor of
22 chiropractic", "practitioner of chiropractic" and "licensee" are
23 synonymous and mean a person holding an original license to practice
24 chiropractic in this state;
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 667 Page 3

1 7. "Examination" means the process used by the Board, prior to
2 the issuance of an original license, to test the qualifications and
3 knowledge of an applicant on any or all of the following: current
4 statutes, rules or any of those subjects listed in Section 161.8 of
5 this title;
6 8. "Intern" means a student at an accredited chiropractic
7 college program who is participating in the Chiropractic
8 Undergraduate Preceptorship Program;
9 9. "Nonclinical" means of a business nature including, but not
10 limited to, practice management, insurance information, and computer
11 information. It shall also mean the discussion of philosophy as it
12 relates to the performance of chiropractic;
13 10. "Original license" means a license granting initial
14 authorization to practice chiropractic in this state issued by the
15 Board to an applicant found by the Board to meet the licensing
16 requirements of the Oklahoma Chiropractic Practice Act, by
17 examination pursuant to Section 161.7 of this title, or by
18 relocation of practice pursuant to Section 161.9 of this title;
19 11. "Preceptor" means a chiropractic physician who is
20 participating in the Chiropractic Undergraduate Preceptorship
21 Program;
22 12. "Relocation of practice" means the recognition and approval
23 by the Board, prior to the issuance of an original license, of the
24
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 667 Page 4

1 chir opractic licensing process in another state, country, territory
2 or province; and
3 13. "Renewal license" means a license issued to a chiropractic
4 physician by the Board, on or before the first day of July of each
5 year, which authorizes such licensee to practice chiropractic in
6 this state during the succeeding calendar year.
7 SECTION 3. AMENDATORY 59 O.S. 2021, Section 161.7, is
8 amended to read as follows:
9 Section 161.7. A. 1. Applications for an original license by
10 examination to practice chiropractic in this state shall be made to
11 the Board of Chiropractic Examiners in writing on a form and in a
12 manner prescribed by the Board through the online licensure portal.
13 2. The application shall be accompanied by a fee of Three
14 Hundred Dollars ($300.00), which shall not be refundable under any
15 circumstances.
16 3. If the application is disapproved by the Board, the
17 applicant shall be so notified by the Executive Director of the
18 Board of Chiropractic Examiners, with the reason for such
19 disapproval fully stated in writing.
20 4. If the application is approved, the applicant may take an
21 examination administered by the Board for the purpose of securing an
22 original license. The Board may accept a passing score on an
23 examination administered by the National Board of Chiropractic
24
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 667 Page 5

1 Exam iners taken by the applicant or may require the applicant to
2 take an examination administered by the Board or both.
3 5. Prior to approval of an application, the Board may authorize
4 the Executive Director of the Board of Chiropractic Examiners to
5 issue a temporary license to an applicant who has submitted a
6 completed application and who, upon payment of the examination fee,
7 has passed the required examination with a score acceptable to the
8 Board. A temporary license shall authorize the applicant to
9 practice chiropractic in Oklahoma between the submission of the
10 application and the applicant's approval for licensure by the Board.
11 A temporary license shall expire upon the Board's approval of a
12 permanent license or ten (10) calendar days following the Board's
13 denial of an application for a permanent license.
14 B. Applicants for an original license to practice chiropractic
15 in this state shall submit to the Board of Chiropractic Examiners
16 documentary evidence of completion of:
17 1. A course of resident study of not less than four (4) years
18 of nine (9) months each in an accredited chiropractic college A
19 valid degree of Doctor of Chiropractic from an accredited program.
20 A senior student at an accredited chiropractic college program may
21 make application for an original license by examination prior to
22 graduation, but such a license shall not be issued until documentary
23 evidence of the graduation of the student from the college program
24 has been submitted to the Board;
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 667 Page 6

1 2. Parts I, II, III, IV and physiotherapy as administered by
2 the National Board of Chiropractic Examiners with a passing score;
3 and
4 3. Passing a jurisprudence examination approved by the Board
5 with a score of seventy-five percent (75%) or better.
6 C. Each applicant shall be a graduate of an accredited
7 chiropractic college program. For those graduating from a
8 chiropractic program outside the United States, the applicants must
9 have completed an educational program leading to a degree in
10 chiropractic from an institution authorized to operate by the
11 government having jurisdiction in which it is domiciled.
12 D. All credentials, diplomas, and other required documentation
13 in a foreign language submitted to the Board by such applicants
14 shall be accompanied by notarized English translations.
15 E. International applicants shall provide satisfactory evidence
16 of meeting the requirements for permanent residence or temporary
17 nonimmigrant status as set forth by the United States Citizenship
18 and Immigration Services.
19 F. Effective January 1, 2006, out-of-state licensed applicants
20 shall submit to the Board documentary evidence that the applicant
21 has malpractice insurance. New applicants shall submit to the Board
22 documentary evidence that the applicant has malpractice insurance
23 within six (6) months of obtaining their his or her Oklahoma
24 license.
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 667 Page 7

1 G. An applicant for an original license shall:
2 1. Inform the Board as to whether the person has previously
3 been licensed in Oklahoma and whether the license was revoked or
4 surrendered;
5 2. Inform the Board as to whether the applicant has ever been
6 licensed in another jurisdiction and whether any disciplinary action
7 was taken against the applicant;
8 3. Provide full disclosure to the Board of any criminal
9 proceeding taken against the applicant including, but not limited
10 to, pleading guilty or nolo contendere to, receiving a deferred
11 sentence for, or being convicted of a felony crime that
12 substantially relates to the practice of chiropractic and poses a
13 reasonable threat to public safety; and
14 4. If requested, appear before the Board for a personal
15 interview.
16 H. No later than one (1) year after receiving a license to
17 practice in Oklahoma, chiropractic physicians shall complete an
18 orientation course of training approved by the Board. The
19 orientation course hours shall count as continuing education credits
20 for the year in which they were earned. An association may provide
21 the orientation course of training.
22 I. The Board may issue an original license to those applicants
23 who have passed the required examination with a score acceptable to
24 the Board and who meet all other requirements set forth by the
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 667 Page 8

1 Boar d. No license fee shall be charged by the Board for the balance
2 of the calendar year in which such a license is issued.
3 J. In addition to an applicant's failure to meet any other
4 requirements imposed by this section or other applicable law, the
5 Board may deny a license or impose probationary conditions if an
6 applicant has:
7 1. Pleaded guilty or nolo contendere to, received a deferred
8 sentence for, or been convicted of a felony crime that substantially
9 relates to the practice of chiropractic and poses a reasonable
10 threat to public safety;
11 2. Been the subject of disciplinary action by the Board; or
12 3. Been the subject of disciplinary action in another
13 jurisdiction.
14 K. As used in this section:
15 1. "Substantially relates" means the nature of criminal conduct
16 for which the person was convicted has a direct bearing on the
17 fitness or ability to perform one or more of the duties or
18 responsibilities necessarily related to the occupation; and
19 2. "Poses a reasonable threat" means the nature of criminal
20 conduct for which the person was convicted involved an act or threat
21 of harm against another and has a bearing on the fitness or ability
22 to serve the public or work with others in the occupation.
23 SECTION 4. AMENDATORY 59 O.S. 2021, Section 161.8, is
24 amended to read as follows:
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 667 Page 9

1 Section 161.8. If an examination is administered by the Board
2 of Chiropractic Examiners, it shall include those technical,
3 professional and practical subjects that relate to the practice of
4 chiropractic including, but not limited to, chiropractic principles,
5 anatomy, histology, physiology, symptomatology, orthopedia,
6 chemistry, spinography, diagnosis, sanitation and hygiene,
7 pathology, public health service and adjustology. The Board shall
8 also examine each applicant in the art of chiropractic adjusting, x-
9 ray, diagnostic laboratory procedures, physiological therapeutics
10 and other subjects taught by accredited chiropractic colleges
11 programs.
12 SECTION 5. AMENDATORY 59 O.S. 2021, Section 161.9, is
13 amended to read as follows:
14 Section 161.9. A. Applications for an original license by
15 relocation of practice to practice chiropractic in this state shall
16 be made to the Board of Chiropractic Examiners in writing on a form
17 and in a manner prescribed by the Board through the online licensure
18 portal. The application shall be accompanied by a fee of Three
19 Hundred Dollars ($300.00), which shall not be refundable under any
20 circumstances. If the application is disapproved by the Board, it
21 shall be returned to the applicant shall be notified by the
22 Executive Director of the Board of Chiropractic Examiners, with the
23 reason for its disapproval fully stated in writing.
24
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 667 Page 10

1 B. The Board may, in its discretion, issue an original license
2 by relocation to practice to an applicant who is currently licensed
3 to practice chiropractic in another state, country, territory or
4 province, upon the following conditions:
5 1. That the applicant is of good moral character;
6 2. That the requirements for licensure in the state, country,
7 territory or province in which the applicant is licensed are deemed
8 by the Board to be equivalent to the requirements for obtaining an
9 original license by examination in force in this state at the date
10 of such license;
11 3. That the applicant has no disciplinary matters pending
12 against him or her in any state, country, territory or province;
13 4. That the license of the applicant was obtained by
14 examination in the state, country, territory or province wherein it
15 was issued, or was obtained by examination of the National Board of
16 Chiropractic Examiners;
17 5. That the applicant passes a jurisprudence examination given
18 by the Board or the National Board of Chiropractic Examiners with a
19 minimum score of seventy-five percent (75%) or better; and
20 6. That the applicant meets all other requirements of the
21 Oklahoma Chiropractic Practice Act.
22 C. Any applicant requesting a license by relocation of practice
23 into Oklahoma shall:
24
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 667 Page 11

1 1. Submit to the Board documentary evidence that the applicant
2 has been in active practice as a chiropractic physician three (3)
3 years immediately preceding the date of the application;
4 2. Provide full disclosure to the Board of any disciplinary
5 action taken against the applicant pursuant to licensure as a
6 chiropractic physician in any state pursuant to licensure and/or
7 criminal proceedings;
8 3. Provide full disclosure to the Board of any criminal
9 proceeding taken against the applicant in any jurisdiction
10 including, but not limited to:
11 a. pleading guilty, pleading nolo contendere, receiving a
12 deferred sentence or being convicted of a felony,
13 b. pleading guilty, pleading nolo contendere, receiving a
14 deferred sentence or being convicted of a misdemeanor
15 involving moral turpitude, or
16 c. pleading guilty, pleading nolo contendere, receiving a
17 deferred sentence or being convicted of a violation of
18 federal or state controlled dangerous substance laws;
19 4. If requested, appear before the Board for a personal
20 interview; and
21 5. Pay an application fee to be set by rule of the Board.
22 D. The Board may authorize the Executive Director of the Board
23 of Chiropractic Examiners to issue a temporary license to an
24 applicant who has submitted a completed application and has passed
